  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Sacrificial Rites for Fallen Soldiers on Cold Food Day
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas, life is bounded—a lament of ancient and modern alike.
    Yet names endure through deeds of loyalty and righteousness.

    You drew your bows with weary sinews,
    Heeding the command to display your strength.
    Among generals fierce as bears and tigers,
    You kindled your spirit before the enemy's gate,
    Falling where courage had blazed its brightest.
    Better to perish on the field of battle
    Than to wither shamefully upon a bed at home.

    Now spring grass greens the empty slopes,
    And orioles sing sweetly through the trees.
    The river flows on, distant and eternal,
    Carrying sorrow without end through its depths.
    Rough mounds lie scattered across the barren earth—
    Who can say if spirits know they are remembered?

    What weighs upon my heart is your former valor,
    What grieves me most is this: that in such tender season,
    The sweetness of spring only deepens the ache.

    I offer this humble wine as libation,
    A comfort for your wandering souls.
    Be like Du Hui, who stood firm against the foe—
    Do not follow the path of Wen Xu, who merely longed for home.
    Those who fulfill their noble purpose
    Accomplish what is called the hidden merit of heaven.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Cold Food Day (寒食) is a traditional Chinese festival observed during early spring, traditionally associated with remembrance of the dead.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Du Hui and Wen Xu are historical references representing contrasting virtues: Du Hui symbolizes steadfast resistance, while Wen Xu represents longing for return and comfort.'
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of bears and tigers (熊羆) evokes martial prowess and fearless commanders, while geese and cranes (鵝鸛) may reference the enemy's position or serve as symbols of the battlefield.
